\hypertarget{what-is-sql}{%
\section{What is SQL?}\label{what-is-sql}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Structured Query Language. Called SEQUEL and developed by IBM
  Corporation in the 1970s
\item
  Remains the standard language for a relational database management
  system.
\item
  It's a DECLARATIVE language
  (\href{https://www.sqlite.org/queryplanner.html}{compute what you want
  to compute not how to compute it})
\item
  Its main job is to define and query databases (i.e., two-dimensional
  tables).
\item
  Great for keeping data type integrity, updating data frequently,
  joining different data sources, and doing quick data analyses
\end{itemize}

Notice the difference between \texttt{dplyr} and \texttt{SQL}?

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{dplyr} works like this:

  \texttt{data} \%\textgreater\% \texttt{select(column)}
  \%\textgreater\% \texttt{filter(condition)} \%\textgreater\%
  \texttt{group\_by(column)} \%\textgreater\%
  \texttt{summarise(aggregation\ (e.g.,\ sum()))} \%\textgreater\%
  \texttt{filter(condition)} \%\textgreater\% \texttt{order\_by()}
\item
  \texttt{SQL} works like this:

  \texttt{SELECT\ column,\ aggregation\ (e.g.,\ count(*))}
  \texttt{FROM\ data} \texttt{WHERE\ condition}
  \texttt{GROUP\ BY\ column} \texttt{HAVING\ condition}
  \texttt{ORDER\ BY\ column}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{data-sets}{%
\section{Data sets}\label{data-sets}}

We use
\href{https://www.transtats.bts.gov/DL_SelectFields.asp?Table_ID=236}{the
flight on-time performance data} from the Bureau of Transpiration
Statistics of the U.S. government. The data goes back to 1987 and its
size is more than 20 gigabytes. For practice, we only use a small subset
of the original data (flight data departing NYC in 2013) provided by
RStudio.

\hypertarget{connect-to-the-database}{%
\subsection{Connect to the database}\label{connect-to-the-database}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  This part draws heavily on the \texttt{dbplyr} package vignette.
\item
  The \texttt{DBI} package provides a client-side interface that allows
  \texttt{dplyr} to work with databases. DBI is automatically installed
  when you installed \texttt{dbplyr}. However, you need to install a
  specific backend engine (a tool for communication between R and a
  database management system) for the database (e.g., \texttt{RMariaDB},
  \texttt{RPostgres}, \texttt{RSQLite}, \texttt{obdc},
  \texttt{bigrquery}). In this workshop, we use SQLite because it is the
  easiest to get started with. Personally, I love PostgreSQL because
  it's an open-source and also powerful to do
  \href{https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/functions.html}{many
  amazing things} (e.g., text mining, geospatial analysis).
\item
  If you want to connect to the database not manually, you can use the
  Connections interface in RStudio.
\item
  Here's \href{https://db.rstudio.com/dbi}{some information} on the
  historical background of the package.
\end{itemize}

\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{contains}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"delay"}\NormalTok{)) }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{show\_query}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## <SQL>
## SELECT `dep_delay`, `arr_delay`
## FROM `flights`
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{mutate-select-as}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{mutate} = \texttt{SELECT}
\texttt{AS}}{mutate = SELECT AS}}\label{mutate-select-as}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{flights }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(distance, air\_time) }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}\StringTok{  }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{speed =}\NormalTok{ distance }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(air\_time }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{60}\NormalTok{)) }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{show\_query}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## <SQL>
## SELECT `distance`, `air_time`, `distance` / (`air_time` / 60.0) AS `speed`
## FROM `flights`
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{filter-where}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{filter} =
\texttt{WHERE}}{filter = WHERE}}\label{filter-where}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{flights }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(month }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, day }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{show\_query}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## <SQL>
## SELECT *
## FROM `flights`
## WHERE ((`month` = 1.0) AND (`day` = 1.0))
\end{verbatim}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Note that R and SQL operators are not exactly alike. R uses
  \texttt{!=} for \texttt{Not\ equal\ to}. SQL uses
  \texttt{\textless{}\textgreater{}} or \texttt{!=}. Furthermore, there
  are some cautions about using \texttt{NULL} (NA; unknown or missing):
  it should be \texttt{IS\ NULL} or \texttt{IS\ NOT\ NULL} not
  \texttt{=NULL} or \texttt{!=NULL}. Finally, some of SQL comparison
  operators are more intuitive than their R counterparts
  (\texttt{WHERE\ student\_ID\ BETWEEN\ 1\ and\ 100}
  \texttt{WHERE\ first\_name\ LIKE\ \textquotesingle{}Jae\textquotesingle{}\ WHERE\ last\_name\ IN\ (\textquotesingle{}Kim\textquotesingle{},\ \textquotesingle{}Lee\textquotesingle{},\ \textquotesingle{}Park\textquotesingle{})}).
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{arrange-order-by}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{arrange} =
\texttt{ORDER\ BY}}{arrange = ORDER BY}}\label{arrange-order-by}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{flights }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{arrange}\NormalTok{(carrier, }\KeywordTok{desc}\NormalTok{(arr\_delay)) }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{show\_query}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## <SQL>
## SELECT *
## FROM `flights`
## ORDER BY `carrier`, `arr_delay` DESC
\end{verbatim}

\texttt{AS} and \texttt{group\ by} =
\texttt{GROUP\ BY}}{summarise = SELECT AS and group by = GROUP BY}}\label{summarise-select-as-and-group-by-group-by}}

\begin{Shaded}

\NormalTok{flights }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group\_by}\NormalTok{(month, day) }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{summarise}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{delay =} \KeywordTok{mean}\NormalTok{(dep\_delay)) }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{show\_query}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## <SQL>
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{mutate} = \texttt{SELECT}
\texttt{AS}}{mutate = SELECT AS}}\label{mutate-select-as-1}}

\texttt{dplyr}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
  \CommentTok{\# DBI}
\KeywordTok{dbGetQuery}\NormalTok{(con, }\StringTok{"SELECT distance, air\_time, distance / air\_time / 60.0 AS speed}
\StringTok{FROM flights"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{\%>\%}
\StringTok{  }\CommentTok{\# dplyr}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{arrange}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{desc}\NormalTok{(air\_time))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{what-we-cant-do}{%
\section{What we can't do}\label{what-we-cant-do}}

Check out the issue section of
\href{https://github.com/ianmcook/queryparser}{\texttt{queryparser}} and
that of
\href{https://github.com/ianmcook/tidyquery/issues}{\texttt{tidyquery}}
to see the latest developments.

\textbf{Limitations}

\begin{verbatim}
- Unions (`LEFT JOIN, INNER JOIN, RIGHT JOIN, CROSS JOIN, FULL OUTER JOIN`). `table1 LEFT JOIN table2 ON table1.shared_column = table2.shared_column`. Usually, 
`SELECT
FROM Unions 
GROUP by 
ORDER BY`
- Subqueries (usually used in a `FROM` or a `WHERE` statement)
`SELECT column
FROM data 
WHERE condition (SELECT column
                 FROM data
                 GROUP BY another column
                 HAVING condition) <- this is subquery`
- WITH clause 
\end{verbatim}
